        <h2>Test and learn fast</h2>
        {# <p>With the regulations having a hard deadline the business needed to be ready for, I ensured we were continuously chatting to our engineers to understand complexity and their timelines.</p>
        <p>I set our team some tight deadlines, giving ourselves 2 weeks to go from low fidelity starter-for-ten to testable prototype. It was important to not impact when the engineers needed to start and I wanted to ensure we were being decisive and understanding any problem areas with our interpretation of the regulations quickly.</p> #}
        <p>With principle-based regulation, there is a certain element of interpretation and I didn't want us to get bogged down with detail. I also wanted our users to tell us where the regulations were actually tripping them up so we could use this as evidence in conversations with the FCA.</p>
        <p>A real sticking point for us as a team during the design process was the demands and needs questions. We started with two radio buttons, went to a decision tree and other simple chaining of questions, but ultimately the weighting factor for either ‘bucket' of options was cost. This felt very opaque to us but the regulations said we weren't allowed to talk about cost before we'd understood the user's needs.</p>
        <p>We split testing over two days, and the first day we weren't surprised to hear cost (or lack of) was a sticking point and a barrier to user's *making an informed choice.* I made a very quick edit to the prototype for day 2, ‘these plans cost more' and ‘these plans cost less' and we saw a marked improvement to a user's understanding. We took this back to our compliance colleagues and asked ‘would showing a *from* price be a problem?' and given the evidence, they felt comfortable with this. We also presented this back to the FCA and it hasn't been a problem given our evidence.</p>
    </div>

